"Magnus J.R., Melenberg B., Muris C.","Global warming and local dimming: The statistical evidence",2011,"Journal of the American Statistical Association","106","494",,"452","468",,,10.1198/jasa.2011.ap09508,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79960115255&partnerID=40&md5=c11cb937dd69c20f057117573cb56981","Department of Econometrics and OR, Tilburg University, P.O. Box 90153, 5000LE Tilburg, Netherlands; University of Göttingen, Wilhelm-Weber- Str. 2, D-37073, Germany","Magnus, J.R., Department of Econometrics and OR, Tilburg University, P.O. Box 90153, 5000LE Tilburg, Netherlands; Melenberg, B., Department of Econometrics and OR, Tilburg University, P.O. Box 90153, 5000LE Tilburg, Netherlands; Muris, C., University of Göttingen, Wilhelm-Weber- Str. 2, D-37073, Germany","Two effects largely determine global warming: the well-known greenhouse effect and the less well-known solar radiation effect. An increase in concentrations of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases contributes to global warming: the greenhouse effect. In addition, small particles, called aerosols, reflect and absorb sunlight in the atmosphere. More pollution causes an increase in aerosols, so that less sunlight reaches the Earth (global dimming). Despite its name, global dimming is primarily a local (or regional) effect. Because of the dimming the Earth becomes cooler: the solar radiation effect. Global warming thus consists of two components: the (global) greenhouse effect and the (local) solar radiation effect, which work in opposite directions. Only the sum of the greenhouse effect and the solar radiation effect is observed, not the two effects separately. Our purpose is to identify the two effects. This is important, because the existence of the solar radiation effect obscures the magnitude of the greenhouse effect. We propose a simple climate model with a small number of parameters. We gather data from a large number of weather stations around the world for the period 1959-2002. We then estimate the parameters using dynamic panel data methods, and quantify the parameter uncertainty. Next, we decompose the estimated temperature change of 0.73°C (averaged over the weather stations) into a greenhouse effect of 1.87°C, a solar radiation effect of -1.09°C, and a small remainder term. Finally, we subject our findings to extensive sensitivity analyses. © 2011 American Statistical Association.","Aerosols; Decomposition; Dynamic panel data; Greenhouse effect; Solar radiation",,,,,,,"Allen, M.R., Gillett, N.P., Kettleborough, J.A., Hegerl, G., Schnur, R., Stott, P.A., Boer, G., Barnett, T.P., Quantifying anthropogenic influence on recent near-surface temperature change (2006) Surveys In Geophysics, 27, pp. 491-544. , [461]; Anderson, T.L., Charlson, R.J., Schwartz, S.E., Knutti, R., Boucher, O., Rodhe, H., Heintzenberg, J., Climate forcing by aerosols- a hazy picture (2003) Science, 300, pp. 1103-1104. , [452,461]; Andreae, M.O., Jones, C.D., Cox, P.M., Strong present-day aerosol cooling implies a hot future (2005) Nature, 435, pp. 1187-1190. , [452,454]; Arellano, M., Bond, S.R., Some tests of specification for panel data: Monte Carlo evidence and an application to employment equations (1991) Review of Economic Studies, 58, pp. 277-297. , [457-459,463]; Bellouin, N., Boucher, O., Haywood, J., Reddy, M.S., Global estimate of aerosol direct radiative forcing from satellite measurements (2005) Nature, 438, pp. 1138-1141. , [452,461]; Blundell, R., Bond, S.R., Initial conditions and moment restrictions in dynamic panel data models (1998) Journal of Econometrics, 87, pp. 115-143. , [457-459]; Budyko, M.I., The effect of solar radiation variations on the climate of the earth (1969) Tellus XXI, 5, pp. 611-619. , [453,456,457]; Crutzen, P.J., Ramanathan, V., The parasol effect on climate (2003) Science, 302, pp. 1678-1680. , [461]; Gilgen, H., Ohmura, A., The global energy balance archive (1999) Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society, 80, pp. 8